Methodology

The Model

The primary prediction model is a Random Forest ensemble (100 trees, mtry=4). We also run Elastic Net in parallel to compare performance over time.

Why Random Forest?

Model comparison on historical data showed:

Model MAE HIGH Conf ROI Notes
Random Forest 5.55 +1.7% Primary model
Elastic Net 5.41 +1.6% Tracked for comparison
XGBoost 5.40 -1.4% Best MAE but worse ROI

Random Forest has slightly higher MAE but better HIGH confidence ROI, which is what matters for betting.

Model Features (12 predictors)

Both models use the same features:

Feature Importance Description
roll_pts_9 High 9-game rolling average points
roll_pts_3 High 3-game rolling average points
career_avg_pts High Career scoring average
roll_pts_7 Medium 7-game rolling average points
roll_pts_5 Medium 5-game rolling average points
roll_mp_3 Medium 3-game rolling average minutes
roll_usg_3 Medium 3-game rolling usage percentage
roll_usg_5 Medium 5-game rolling usage percentage
roll_pts_sd_5 Low 5-game scoring variance (consistency)
roll_3pa_3 Low 3-game rolling 3-point attempts
days_rest Low Days since last game
roll_mp_5 Low 5-game rolling average minutes

Why These Features Matter

  • Rolling averages dominate: The model heavily weights recent performance (9-game average is most important)
  • Career average anchors predictions: Players tend to regress toward their long-term mean
  • Minutes predict points: More playing time = more scoring opportunities
  • Consistency matters: High variance scorers are harder to predict

Backtest Process

The backtest simulates what would have happened if we followed different betting strategies.

Step 1: Data Collection

  • Betting lines: 427,579 player point prop lines from The Odds API (7 major sportsbooks)
  • Player stats: 310,000+ player-game records from Basketball Reference
  • Matched records: 56,264+ games where we have both a prediction and betting lines

Step 2: Generate Predictions

For each player-game, the Random Forest model predicts expected points using the features above. All features use lagged data (we only know what happened before the game). We also generate Elastic Net predictions for comparison tracking.

Step 3: Calculate Edge

Edge = Model Prediction - Vegas Line
  • Positive edge: Model thinks player will score MORE than the line (bet OVER)
  • Negative edge: Model thinks player will score LESS than the line (bet UNDER)

Step 4: Apply Betting Rules

For each strategy, we filter bets by:

  1. Edge threshold: Only bet when |edge| >= X points (e.g., 3 points)
  2. Odds threshold: Only bet when odds >= Y (e.g., -115 or better)
  3. Bet type: Over, Under, or best available

Step 5: Calculate P&L

For each qualifying bet:

  • Win: Payout based on American odds (e.g., -115 pays $86.96 on $100 bet)
  • Loss: Lose $100 stake
  • Push: Line equals actual points, bet returned

Step 6: Aggregate Results

  • ROI = Total P&L / Total Amount Wagered
  • Win Rate = Wins / Total Bets

Why Unders Win

The backtest consistently shows UNDERS outperform OVERS. Why?

  1. Regression to the mean: Hot streaks dont last. If a player scored 35 points last game, theyre more likely to score closer to their average next game.

  2. Injury/rest effects: Players often sit out or play limited minutes, resulting in under their line.

  3. Line-setting bias: Sportsbooks may shade lines toward overs because casual bettors like betting on points being scored.

  4. Our model captures this: The large positive coefficient on career_avg_pts (0.465) pulls predictions toward long-term averages, naturally favoring unders after hot streaks.

The Vig Problem

Player prop odds are NOT -110 (the standard). They average -135 to -170.

Win Rate Needed At Odds
52.4% -110
53.5% -115
56.5% -130
60.0% -150
66.7% -200

At -135 average odds, you need to win 57.4% just to break even. The model wins 55-56% - barely profitable at average odds.

Solution: Only bet when you find odds of -115 or better through line shopping.

Walk-Forward Validation

To ensure no look-ahead bias, we run a walk-forward backtest that retrains the model every week:

  1. Train on all data before Week N
  2. Predict Week N games
  3. Add Week N results to training data
  4. Repeat for Week N+1

This simulates real-world usage where youd retrain periodically with new data.

Walk-Forward Results (UNDERS at -105 odds)

Edge Threshold Bets Win Rate ROI
3.0 points 1,220 56.1% +15.6%
2.5 points 1,672 55.4% +14.9%
4.0 points 701 55.9% +13.6%
2.0 points 2,230 53.5% +11.7%

Key Finding: Strong profitability across all thresholds.
